---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Divorce Settlements</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Uncontested divorce</h2><p>Both spouses agree on all terms. Fastest, cheapest, least adversarial. Works well when assets are simple, marriage is short, and both parties communicate cooperatively. Legal fees: $1,000&ndash;$3,000 total.</p>
  <h2>Mediated divorce</h2><p>A neutral mediator helps spouses reach agreement. Not binding until formalized in a court-approved agreement. More flexible and less expensive than litigation ($3,000&ndash;$10,000 total). Requires both parties to negotiate in good faith.</p>
  <h2>Collaborative divorce</h2><p>Each spouse has an attorney trained in collaborative law. Both attorneys commit to reaching a settlement outside court. If negotiation fails, both must hire new attorneys for litigation. Cost: $15,000&ndash;$30,000 per spouse for complex estates.</p>
  <h2>Litigated divorce</h2><p>Judge decides all contested issues at trial. Most expensive and emotionally draining. Average cost for fully litigated divorces: $15,000&ndash;$50,000 per spouse. Courts have broad discretion, which makes outcomes less predictable.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-divorce-asset-division-works">how asset division works</a> and <a href="/guides/spousal-support-guide">spousal support guide</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
